                <h2>Landscape and Beaches</h2>

                <h3 class="text-justify">The Bahamas</h3>
                <p class="text-justify">The Bahamas has more than 700 islands, islets, and cays with few inhabitants. Travelers will particularly enjoy the constant sunshine, the stunning anchorages, the world-famous sand beaches, and clear and shallow waters that allow them to appreciate the natural beauty of the archipelago better. </p>

                <ul>
                    <li>The Grand Bahamas is better known for its underwater caves, snorkel, and dive sites. </li>
                    <li>The island also has the Lucayan National Park, the Abacos for the beaches, sheltered bays and coves, lush green forest, and superb tourist diving spots. </li>
                    <li>Eleuthera is known for its endless beaches and coral reefs, making it an excellent place for tourists to dive and snorkel. </li>
                    <li>Harbour Island has a beautiful three-mile pink sand beach rated within the world's top ten beaches. </li>
                </ul>

                <p class="text-justify">The long white sand beaches of the Bahamas are hard to find in the Caribbean. </p>

                <h3 class="text-justify">The Caribbean</h3>
                <p class="text-justify">
                    Just like the Bahamas, beautiful beaches and the warm blue sea are the best assets of the Caribbean. However, the island has much more to offer. You can see lush forests, tropical jungle-covered volcanoes, endemic plants, fascinating animals, and an incredible seabed. The scenery of the Caribbean is too unique and beautiful.
                </p>
                <ul>
                    <li>The Windward Islands and their jungle-covered volcanoes slope to the emerald green seas. </li>
                    <li>You can also find the Baths National Park with a collection of massive granite boulders, which are as large as 40 feet in diameter and consist of white sand beaches and private rock pools. </li>
                    <li>The island also has Antigua and its 365 beaches which offer the best sailing. </li>
                    <li>Mount Scenery is perfect for hiking, and its colourful coral reefs enhance its beauty. </li>
                    <li>Tourists have much more places to explore, like St Vincent and the Grenadines and its rainforest, waterfalls, deserted beaches, secluded coves, and much more. </li>
                </ul>

                <p class="text-justify">The turquoise beaches in the Caribbean are much more diverse than the beaches in the Bahamas. </p>


                <h3>Bahamas’ Culture</h3>

                <p class="text-justify">The Bahamas has a distinct culture that has evolved over the past years. The culture mainly came from Africa, mixed with British and American influences. The Bahamas remained a British colony till its independence. The English language and Protestantism are leading British cultural contributions to the island. </p>

                <p class="text-justify">
                    The island predominantly comprises the descendants of Africans, and there is an influence of African culture. Goombay, Rake 'n' Scrape, and Junkanoo are some of the island's music cultures. Dances, folktales, myths, and stories are other cultures passed down through generations.
                </p>
                <h3>Caribbean’s Culture</h3>

                <p class="text-justify">The Caribbean is an island of various cultures, languages, architecture, cuisine, customs, music, and many more. The region offers more than 22 UNESCO World Heritage sites one must visit. The people here are vibrant and colourful. </p>

                <p class="text-justify">Joie de vivre is held during the Carnival, an essential part of culture celebrated by most islands. The culture of the Caribbean is a rich mix of colonial and native constituents, which is adapted to the specific history of each country. The diversity of the Caribbean region gives a unique identity to the area. </p>


                <h4>Activities offered in the Bahamas</h4>
                <p class="text-justify">The Bahamas has 700 islands and is the world's third-largest barrier Reef. With countless blue holes and coral reefs, it undoubtedly provides the best diving destination for tourists. The Bahamas is naturally an ideal destination for water activities. </p>

                <ul>
                    <li>The Blue Lagoon has established itself as one of the top family attractions in the Bahamas. </li>
                    <li>You can walk the endless Segway tracks, surrounded by coastal coconut palm groves and an inland lagoon packed with wildlife and water sports opportunities. </li>
                    <li>Blue lagoon is the home of the Dolphin Encounter program, and travellers can get a chance to swim with the dolphins. </li>
                    <li>You can also go beachcombing and caving in the Lucayan National Park. Travellers can also enjoy cycling paths, water sports, basketball courts and snorkelling, beaches, and restaurants. </li>
                    <li>Stocking Island is perfect for tourists who have come for a coastal hike. </li>
                    <li>The Bahamas has some of the best resorts with great activities and tours and the best pools. </li>
                    <li>There is no shortage of snorkelling and scuba diving sites around the archipelago of the Bahamas. Try diving in the waters around Andros. </li>
                </ul>

                <h4>Activities offered in the Caribbean</h4>
